@*
    09. Scoped panels — multiple selects, each one applies to <html>.

    Note: unlike the Vue helper, the Blazor LocaleSelect always writes
    lang/dir to <html> (no per-panel `target` parameter). For per-region
    scoping you can use multiple selects with distinct Names, but they
    will fight over <html>. To get true per-region behaviour, wrap each
    panel and write its own lang/dir via OnChange, leaving the document
    root alone (pass ApplyDir="false" and write lang yourself).

    This example shows two selects that share <html>, with the last
    selection winning. For region-scoped state without DOM conflicts,
    use distinct StorageKey values per panel.
*@

@page "/examples/locale-select/scoped-target"
@rendermode InteractiveServer
@using LilyDesignSystem.Blazor.Helpers

<article>
    <h1>Document language is shared; each panel tracks its own select value.</h1>

    <section class="panel">
        <h2>Panel A</h2>
        <LocaleSelect
            Label="Panel A language"
            Name="panel-a-locale"
            Locales="@(new[] { "en", "fr", "ar" })"
            StorageKey="panel-a"
            @bind-Value="aLocale" />
        <p>Current Panel A locale: <code>@aLocale</code></p>
    </section>

    <section class="panel">
        <h2>Panel B</h2>
        <LocaleSelect
            Label="Panel B language"
            Name="panel-b-locale"
            Locales="@(new[] { "en", "fr", "ar" })"
            StorageKey="panel-b"
            @bind-Value="bLocale" />
        <p>Current Panel B locale: <code>@bLocale</code></p>
    </section>
</article>

@code {
    private string aLocale = "en";
    private string bLocale = "fr";
}
